    <name>GIOTTO</name>
    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>GIO</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Giotto spacecraft was designed for a joint space mission to achieve a fly-by of comet Halley in 1985 and later rendezvous with comet Tempel 2 in 1988. Initially part of a collaboration with NASA, the mission shifted to a solely European endeavor due to funding issues. Giotto was developed using a spin-stabilized design based on the Geos concept, permitting protection and stability during high-speed fly-bys. It carried ten scientific instruments for studying cometary components and offered data transmission capabilities. The spacecraft featured a unique dust shield to protect against high-velocity dust impacts, critical for maintaining communication with Earth during encounters. Despite experiencing some instrument malfunctions during its operations, many of Giotto's components continued to function effectively post-encounter. The mission successfully launched on July 2, 1985.</description>
  </Instrument_Host>
